6. Summis verticibus] This has been variously explained. Bentley supposes it to mean the heads of the nails‚ “when Fate drives in the nails to the heads.” His note on these lines is one of his worst. Some take Horace to mean that Fate, by driving her nails (‘clavos trabales‚’ i. 35. 18) into the ro'of of the house, puts an end to the work and declares that the master-'s work is done. Such is the meaning Orelli gives, and he supposes Horace to have got the idea from some Greek poet. The Scho- liasts throw no light upon it.
